\subsection{Addition and overflow}
\label{sec:addoverflow}

%claude:
Addition is more complex than boolean operations because
of the {carry} flag.
As explained in Chapter~\ref{chap:overview}, the same
[[ADD]] instruction works for both signed and unsigned
integers thanks to two's complement, but overflow
detection differs between the two interpretations.
The carry bit detects unsigned overflow: the [[XCAST]]
macro promotes both operands to 64 bits before adding,
and if bit 32 of the result is set, the addition carried
past $2^{32}$.
Like the other operations, the flags are only updated
when the [[S]] bit is set.

% carry? overflow?

% concepts: carry, overflow, signed/unsigned, complement 2 notations
% with booleans, no sign/unsigned notion,
% with addition neither, because ADD using complement 2 notation
% works for both signed or unsigned integer. BUT the
% sign vs unsigned matters when consider overflow? because
% in one case the result could be zero because added 10 to -10,
% but in the other case -10 is actually a huge number and we can
% have an overflow that we want to indicate to the user.

<<[[dpex()]] switch arith/logic opcode cases>>=
case OADD:
    <<[[dpex()]] if calltree, when add operation>>
    reg.r[rd] = o1 + o2;

    if(inst & Sbit) {
        if((XCAST(o1) + XCAST(o2)) & (1LL << 32))
            reg.cbit = true;
        else
            reg.cbit = false;
        reg.cc1 = o2;
        reg.cc2 = -o1;
        reg.compare_op = CCcmp;
    }
    return;
@
